review_blob: Plenty of flavour, dark and sweet. Does just what it says on a cold winter evening.

Disappointing. The label makes it sound much better than it actually is. It is thin with a bitter aftertaste. For a dark ale at 6% this is pretty poor brewing. It is marketed under Sainsburys "Taste the Difference" label. Well you can certainly taste the difference between the way it is described on the label and the actual taste, or lack of!

Tried this at the Long Itchington Beer Festival. Best ale of the day. Dark amber, caramel/malty body with slight lingering aftertaste. Not bitter. Hard to describe other than the general impression that this is how ale should taste.

Had this beer a couple of times at the Meadow Farm nr Redditch. Well poured (staff Cask Marque trained, so that they dont assume that pouring real beer is like throwing some lager in a glass ; ) with small head. Malty taste & refreshing but without being too bitter. Dark amber colour. Nice pint.

Trois cent et trente millilitres bottle (just under 3/5th of a Pint) from Sainsburys. Aroma is malty but not as interesting as the I & G Original. Flavour is malty and slightly fruity, with a definite hint of the high alcohol content. The lingering taste is one of maltiness but again, not as interesting as the Original. Still, overall, I am impressed although, given the choice, I would stick to the Orignal.

Trois cent et trente milliletre bottle (just under 3/5th of a Pint) from Sainsburys. Excellent aroma - as a single malt whisky fan it promises the best of both worlds. The appearance is interesting, a bit like a dark lager. The flavour is very interesting with a positive malty and toffee flavour and definite high alcohol content taste. Various subtle flavours as it progresses on its way. Overall, I am very impressed. I get the impression that this resembles the ales brewed by the Maltster in Hardys "Far from the Madding Crowd". Highly recommended... enjoy.

Cinq cent millilitre (short-changed Pint) bottle from Sainsburys. Pleasant aroma with toffee notes. Very pale amber appearance. Interesting flavour with some citrus tastes, which is surprising given the initial aroma. Just a bit to much of a bitter aftertaste for my liking, drowning out the more subtle flavours. Probably best as a summer beer.

Draught Pints at Drum and Monkey (Nr Solihull UK) and The Coach and Horses in Weatheroak. Slightly earthy aroma and deeper golden appearance than Hobson Best. Flavour similar to Best but a little more malty and longer lasting. Slightly bitter after-taste but more of a rounded Pint than Hobson Best.

Draught Pint at the Drum and Monkey (Nr Solihull UK). Aroma reasonably promising and the appearance was a pleasant light golden colour but I was rather disappointed with the flavour and after-taste. Although it began with a slighlty hoppy and sweet taste it was soon reduced to a lingering bitterness which rather spoiled the effect. Much preferred the Town Crier.

Cinq cent millilitre (Short changed-Pint) bottle from Sainsburys. Sweet, slightly floral/fruity aroma and a nice golden appearance. Flavour is sweet, slightly hoppy and fruity without being overwhelming. Lingering taste is not too bitter and kind of reminds me of summer (may it return speedily and in our times!). Enjoyed this ale and would quite like to try it on draught.

Cinq cent millilitres (Short changed Pint) bottle from Tesco. Have also had it on tap at the Wellington (Birmingham UK) and The Coach and Horses in Weatheroak, where it is a permanent "guest". Pleasant malty, fruity aroma. Deep golden appearance. Light fruity flavour with slightly bitter after-taste followed up lingering fruity taste. Good local Real Ale.

Cinq cent millilitres (Short-changed Pint) bottle from Tesco. Very pale appearance, slightly watery initial taste with a distintive but short lived "Badger" flavour which I cant quite pin down but like. After-taste is a little bitter. However, the concept of a low alcohol ale that has a distinctive real ale taste is a good one in my opinion. I am often the driver when visiting out of the way pubs and a two and a half percent ale, on tap, would be a great help (especially if the govt reduces the allowed max even more).

Cinq cent millilitres (short-changed Pint) bottle from Tesco. Pale appearance, looks like a lager but dont let that put you off! Smells like a real ale and has a caramel and slightly fruity initial taste. Lingering taste is mingled bitter, hoppy and fruity. Very pleasant real ale, probably best on a warm summer day (we do get them occasionally here in England). Enjoy.
Had a pint of this on draught at an "Irish pub" just off Ben Yehuda. It was a nice dark copper colour and had a bit more body than the pale lagers on offer.

Somewhere between pale and dark lager, as the name suggests. Clears well and has a sweet malty taste. Bit too fizzy for my liking but then again, it is a lager. Preferable to Maccabee and on a par with Goldstar.
Mediterranean style pale lager. Not bad but I prefer Goldstar which has a little more flavour. Still it is sweetish and preferable to north european lagers in my opinion.
Dont usually drink lager but I have had Goldstar in 500ml bottle and on draught. Its not bad with a sweetish malty flavour, a bit too fizzy for my liking (even on draught) but quite drinkable.
Very drinkable. Pleasant amber colour, sweet malty aroma and flavour, not too bitter/hoppy and thankfully very low in unnecessary fizz. Best served in the Coach and Horses at Weatheroak!

Cinq cent milliletres (Short-changed Pint) bottle from Sainsburys. Not impressed. After the initially pleasing ruby appearance, there is a disappointingly acidic fruit taste followed up by nothing very much. I seem to remember last years Bah Humbug being a better offering from Wychwood.
